{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"490db86e-4aea-44a1-9e33-54d6c5170bf0","content":"\n\n`SafeAreaEdges` isn't the right property. You need a combination of platform-specific settings:\n\n**1. iOS** — disable safe area insets on the page:\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n\n<ContentPage ...\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**2. Android** — enable edge-to-edge in your `MainActivity.cs`:\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    if (Window != null)\n    {\n        Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n    }\n}\n```\n(Requires `using AndroidX.Core.View;`)\n\n**3. Hide Shell chrome** (if using `AppShell`):\n```xml\nShell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\nShell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n```\n\n**4. Image should fill the space:**\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nThe most common culprit is #1 on iOS and #2 on Android — `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` is the iOS equivalent of what you were trying to do, and Android requires explicit opt-in to draw behind system bars.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1682d330-7eeb-4fc2-85cb-bbbf70e2ddb1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working on a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. In .NET MAUI, `IgnoreSafeArea` is the property on views to make them extend into safe area insets. But there's also page-level configuration.\n\n2. On **iOS**, you need to set `Page.IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` or use platform-specific APIs. Actually, in .NET MAUI, the way to ignore safe areas is typically through the `IgnoreSafeArea` property on the layout/view.\n   \n3. On **Android**, the approach is different—you need to enable edge-to-edge rendering and configure the window to draw behind system bars, which typically involves platform-specific setup in the Android project to handle window insets properly.\n\nFor .NET MAUI specifically, I'm realizing the actual API surface is more limited than I initially thought. The `IgnoreSafeArea` property doesn't exist as a standard MAUI property, and while iOS has the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` platform configuration available, Android requires more involved setup. The `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` the user mentioned might not be a real MAUI property either—I need to verify what the actual cross-platform solution is in .NET 10. I'm realizing the core issues: on iOS they need to disable safe area handling, on Android they need edge-to-edge configuration with transparent system bars, and they might need to hide Shell navigation elements if they're using that. The `Image` control also needs `AspectFill` to properly fill the screen without gaps.","outputTokens":1465},"id":"86f361ee-a91f-4e35-99c5-3441a746ac76","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:48:49.601Z","parentId":"743b14e8-e89e-4067-9f04-468a7e5261c5"}
